<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,222,463]" pageId="19" pageNumber="490">
SCC identified a specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1937" box="[491,577,223,246]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Platylesches" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rasta">
<emphasis box="[491,577,223,246]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="490">P. rasta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
amongst adults of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wallengren)" authorityName="Wallengren" box="[792,1059,222,247]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Platylesches" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moritili">
<emphasis box="[792,904,222,247]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="490">P. moritili</emphasis>
(Wallengren)
</taxonomicName>
f. 
<emphasis box="[1091,1147,222,247]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="490">delta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cock" box="[1162,1429,222,247]" pageId="19" pageNumber="490" refString="Cock, M. J. W. &amp; Congdon, T. C. E. (2013) Observations on the biology of Afrotropical Hesperiidae (Lepidoptera) principally from Kenya. Part 5. Hesperiinae incertae sedis: Dicotyledon feeders. Zootaxa, 3724 (1), 1 - 85. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3724.1.1" type="journal article" year="2013">Cock &amp; Congdon 2013</bibRefCitation>
) that TCEC reared from 
<taxonomicName box="[422,673,258,283]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chrysobalanaceae" genus="Parinari" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="19" pageNumber="490" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="curatellifolia">
<emphasis box="[422,673,258,283]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="490">Parinari curatellifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from ‘Mulanje Pond’, under Mlanje Mountain, Malawi, an area of rough scrub near the murram road to Mount Zion from Mulanje town. At the time it was assumed to be a lightly marked individual of 
<taxonomicName box="[393,624,330,355]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Platylesches" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moritili">
<emphasis box="[393,624,330,355]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="490">Platylesches moritili</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
f. 
<emphasis box="[654,710,330,355]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="490">delta</emphasis>
and it was only by chance that this individual was photographed (Figure 20.3). The caterpillar must have been a tube maker (
<bibRefCitation author="Cock" box="[831,1216,366,391]" pageId="19" pageNumber="490" refString="Cock, M. J. W. &amp; Congdon, T. C. E. (2013) Observations on the biology of Afrotropical Hesperiidae (Lepidoptera) principally from Kenya. Part 5. Hesperiinae incertae sedis: Dicotyledon feeders. Zootaxa, 3724 (1), 1 - 85. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3724.1.1" type="journal article" year="2013">Cock &amp; Congdon 2013, Figure 70</bibRefCitation>
) and the pupa must have been plain white (
<bibRefCitation author="Cock" box="[423,847,402,427]" pageId="19" pageNumber="490" refString="Cock, M. J. W. &amp; Congdon, T. C. E. (2013) Observations on the biology of Afrotropical Hesperiidae (Lepidoptera) principally from Kenya. Part 5. Hesperiinae incertae sedis: Dicotyledon feeders. Zootaxa, 3724 (1), 1 - 85. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3724.1.1" type="journal article" year="2013">Cock &amp; Congdon 2013, Figure 76.4</bibRefCitation>
) or they would have been noticed as different and documented.
</paragraph>
